'''Banjarbaru''' is a city in the province of [[South Kalimantan]] in [[Indonesia]]. It is located {{convert|35|km|mi}} southeast of [[Banjarmasin]]. The city had a population of 199,627 as of the 2010 Census and 233,726 at the 2015 Census, and the latest official estimate (as at 2017) is 248,423.<ref>Badan Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2018.</ref> The town of [[Martapura, South Kalimantan|Martapura]] lies immediately to the north of Banjarbaru, and in effect constitutes an extension of the city.
==Orientation== Banjarbaru City is located on the major road crossing South Kalimantan. The central road Jalan Jendral Achmad Yani, splits Banjarbaru into two parts. The city is bordered by Martapura (which lies immediately adjacent) to the north, Karang Intan to the east, Gambut and Aluh-Aluh to the west and Bati–Bati (Tanah Laut District) to the south.
==Geography== Banjarbaru is located at the foot of the [[Meratus Mountains]], with 80% of the city area elevated between 0 and {{convert|25|m|ft}} above sea level, but also includes areas up to {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=on}} high. Similarly slopes vary between 0 and 8% for most of the city's territory, with some areas sloping up to 15%.{{citation needed|date=May 2013}}
==Economy== The main economic activities in order of their contribution to the ''Regional Bruto Product'' are: Commerce, restaurant and hotel (21.7%), Services (16.3%), Building (16.3%), Processing industry (15.7%) and Mining: (8.7%), while Agriculture only contributes 4.9%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://en.banjarbarukota.go.id/site/content/view/17/32/ |title=Banjarbaru economic sectors 2005 |access-date=2009-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110312112336/http://en.banjarbarukota.go.id/site/content/view/17/32/ |archive-date=2011-03-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>
==Administration== Banjarbaru has an area of {{convert|371.3|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, divided into five [[Districts of Indonesia|districts]] (''kecamatan''): Banjarbaru Utara (North Banjarbaru), Banjarbaru Selatan (South Banjarbaru), Cempaka, Landasan Ulin and Liang Anggang; currently these districts each cover four administrative villages (''kelurahan''), as set out below with their 2010 Census populations:<ref>Biro Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2011.</ref>
Landasan Ulin District: * Landasan Ulin Timur (14,178) * Guntung Payung (6,474) * Guntung Manggis (19,970) * Syamsuddin Noor (10,888)
Liang Anggang District: * Landasan Ulin Tengah (9,230) * Landasan Ulin Utara (13,303) * Landasan Ulin Barat (6,323) * Landasan Ulin Selatan (5,692)
Cempaka District: * Palam (3,101) * Bangkal (4,217) * Sungai Tiung (7,986) * Cempaka (13,015)
Banjarbaru Utara District: * Loktabat Utara (17,580) * Mentaos (9,431) * Komet (4,019) * Sungai Ulin (11,775)
Banjarbaru Selatan District: * Loktabat Selatan (8,360) * Kemuning (8,495) * Guntung Paikat (7,975) * Sungai Besar (17,615)
